Credit to @beardpreneur (great name, seriously)

#chatgpt #llm #aitool #aitools #aihack #claude #openai

I’ve built a whole team who analyse and report and have conversations between themselves. When I want them to looks at something I tell chat let team x (10 members) have a look and see what they can do. We develop that further and then I’ll say let the extended team x (5 members) have a look and they they do a different deep dive.
How exactly are you creating the bot 🤖? How do you make changes to that bot to make it better?
It functions below the level of a day 1 analyst

Yes, but who’s saying that he needs his COO not to do that? Seems to me that you would have the bot do all task necessary to get you to the point of needing “personhood” then you would step in to finalize the deal. Definitely not a thing right now, but it will be.

The premise of this video suggests that an entire C-suite could be built using AI agents. However, my point is that an AI agent cannot legally be designated as a corporate officer or fulfill the statutory duties required of one. Another example being that state charters require corporate officers be natural living persons. That said, a COO could certainly leverage AI tools to automate routine tasks but that’s what their executive admin’s do.

Good point—AI can’t legally hold corporate officer positions under current laws. But as AI advances, do you think we’ll see a shift where AI-driven decision-making plays a larger role in executive strategy, even if a human remains the official officer? The way AI is already streamlining operations, it seems like the line between AI tools and leadership influence is blurring.

It reminds me of how the internet has completely changed the way businesses operate. There was a time when things like banking, shopping, and even board meetings had to be done in person. Now, remote teams, digital contracts, and virtual decision-making are the norm. AI seems like the next evolution of that—handling tasks that once required human oversight. Maybe we won’t see AI ‘CEOs’ anytime soon, but it’s hard to ignore how technology is redefining leadership and efficiency.
 This response was generated 100% by AI

If you have held a top management position, you understand the legal constructs that prevent an AI agent from performing tyoical COO responsibilities. For example, an AI lacks legal personhood, meaning it cannot enter into binding agreements, assume fiduciary duties, or be held accountable for business decisions--fundamental aspects of executive leadership.
